##95 post-first-line nurse: Sunflower in Wuhan Ward

Micro signal

Function description, we are with you in this battle

She'll cry because she's homesick, and she'll be happy because she's had a coke. She volunteered to serve patients on the Wuhan Front Line, and I admire her strong and brave.

By Wu Meifen

Xiao Kui, a 24-year-old nurse, traveled from Beijing to Wuhan to support her. It has been 20 days since she arrived in Wuhan on February 7. On February 19, I contacted her through Weng Wen, a family member of the patient I had interviewed earlier. On February 22, Xiaokui gave an interview to me on her rest day to talk about her experience in supporting the intensive care unit in Wuhan.

Small Sunflower in Wuhan is the service of patients with severe illness, the daily intensity of work is very large. One day, because of menstrual discomfort, she fainted in the ward, was supported by colleagues out of the ward. After a little recovery, she said: "Good Gas AH! Wasted a suit of protective clothing, did not let it play a big role. " She Love Protective Clothing, I love her.

Let's hope the epidemic is over and the lovely girls go home.

Here's what she said:

Three times he volunteered to support Wuhan

New Year 28, the hospital let the ward selected to Wuhan Support Nurses, the head nurse first in the emergency team in the month to choose. I wasn't in the echelon. The office gave me the names of the other two nurses. But one of the nurses had a child, and the other had just gotten married and was trying to have a baby. I'm not married, I don't have kids, and my family supports me. I'll tell the chief that my name will be used in our department.

The first support team from our hospital set out on the first day of the New Year. I signed up but failed. It wasn't my turn until the third batch. First, the hospital is from the respiratory intensive care unit, Intensive Care Unit, infectious diseases and emergency departments, and several other departments priority to send support. I'm in hematology, so I'm a little behind.

I grew up in grandma's side, the first two registration did not dare to tell her, for fear that she can not eat, sleep well, just talked with their parents. After the third time, I told grandma. The grandmother was very strong, she said: "I have guessed, you should take the responsibility as a nurse. You should go, don't worry at home. "

February 7 at 5:00 am, in order to leave on time, the department head arranged a special car to pick me up at home, my boyfriend accompanied to the hospital gate. We've only been dating for ten days, and it's a shame we didn't spend our first Valentine's Day together. At the send-off, he said he'd buy me a present when I got back.

By the time we got to Beijing Capital International Airport, we'd already seen support teams from a bunch of hospitals in the city, and there were three people on the same flight as us.

It took off at 10:30, and about two hours later, we landed at Wuhan Tianhe Airport.

You feel the difference as soon as you step off the plane. It is sunny in Beijing and cloudy in Wuhan. When the bus picked us up on the road, there were no people in the street, and an empty city was filled with the feeling of a biological crisis. The car we were in smelled of disinfectant, and the driver was wearing protective clothing and gloves.

The sight made me nervous.

"I'm pretty excited about my first day off. "

On February 10th, I entered the ward for the first time. I was working with a senior cardio nurse that day, going from 35 to 56. All the beds in the ward were full, and several patients were put on non-invasive breathing machines.

It took me almost an hour to put on my hazmat suit before I entered the ward. The teacher in charge of feeling control has been carefully check, see a little exposed to take tape to help me stick, make sure no exposure to wear the next.

Sunflower is in Sick Bay

My goggles fogged when I entered the ward before I had any experience. I couldn't read the names on the list, so I had to look up and down to get a relatively clear view, and then ask the patients'names one by one to check, so the work was slow and took about two hours.

The most impressive are beds 55 and 56, a young couple. Every time we take a vital signs test, no matter who we give it to first, the other side gets nervous. Test the female patient first, the male patient will be very nervous, constantly ask her how? And vice versa. They were really close, and now they're almost ready to leave the hospital.

One of our patients is an 88-year-old grandmother. As soon as she saw US enter the room, she rushed to hug us, but we had to keep our distance from the patient to avoid infection. We just sit her down and tell her she can't hold her right now. She gave a thumbs-up and said a lot of words of thanks in a hurry, all in dialect, some of which we did not understand. A lot of patients do. They thank us all the time.

After my first day off, I was excited. I didn't feel tired. After returning to the hotel, received a lot of social donations of goods, milk, coffee, fruit, snacks and so on. I ate a bunch of random snacks, and I didn't even eat.

A memorable Valentine's Day and Lantern Festival

On February 13, I started a four-hour shift, from 1:00 a.m. to 5:00 a.m. , which was always three hours. That day many patients were found on the breathing machine, we are responsible for the front of the bed number of a group of patients, are relatively severe symptoms of the 70-80-year-old.

There is a grandmother is in a critical state, consciousness is a little unclear, a little agitated. I had never seen such a large formation, a particularly large non invasive breathing machine, with an oxygen tank about my height beside it, feeding her through both Oxygenation, barely 80% .

She's a little fat, won't let us change her diapers, and it's hard to change her sheets. We were concerned that the stool would stay long enough to become infected, so we insisted on replacing it. It took the four of us about half an hour to change the sheets and put her in a diaper.

Many people change the bed sheets for the patients

Four-hour shifts are different than three, especially after the day I helped that grandmother change her sheets. I wore three layers of gloves, each layer of clothes inside the extra tight, coupled with tightly wrapped tape, after work found that his hands lack of blood supply, hair white bilge. There was also a ligature mark on his wrist and a deep earth-red mark on his face.

Back at the hotel after showering, over an hour later, the mark didn't even go down. It took me almost 12 hours of sleep to wake up that day.

I woke up on February 14th, Valentine's Day.

After I arrived in Wuhan, I had to call my family every day to tell them that I was safe. I would also report that I was safe in the hospitals in Beijing. That night, the weather was fine, and we got a new shipment of protective equipment. In the field of goods and materials, I saw someone with chocolate put a "XX hospital refueling" model, and a love.

Later, I saw the image of this shape in various groups went viral, received a lot of likes and praise. It happened to be a sunny day after rain in Wuhan, which was particularly exciting.

A heart made of chocolate

February 15, heavy snow in Wuhan, we work in the ward feeling very cold. Because the central air-conditioning will carry the spread of germs, resulting in more people cross-infection, can not open. To keep the air clean, the windows in the work area were wide open, so cold that my hands wouldn't bend when I stuck a needle in a patient's arm. We wear protective clothing into the ward to work a circle, full of sweat, the wind blows even colder.

This Day, said 88-year-old grandmother discharged from the hospital. This grandma state of mind is particularly good, when we came, she did not how injection infusion, only take oral medicine and the like of proprietary Chinese medicine, nucleic acid test turned negative, CT is also nothing. She set a new record for the oldest discharge from our hospital.

After work back to the hotel, because too many people hot water supply is not stable, I took a cold shower. We have to shower every day, and we have to do it for more than 30 minutes a day to get rid of the germs we carry.

On Feb. 15, the Lantern Festival, our leaders posted a video on the wechat group, which was recorded by our colleagues, friends and family in Beijing, as well as in our hematology department's The Adventure of the Resident Patient.

One child, a year and a half old, has just had a bone marrow transplant. In the video, he gives us his best wishes in a cute voice. I watched the video several times, and I cried every time.

"I'm starting to miss home. "

Gradually, we face more and more serious patients, many people need to be inserted needle, gastric tube, catheter, almost all patients need oxygen support. The oxygen in the hospital is unstable, and the workload is getting worse.

New cases are coming in by the thousands every day, and our first responders have been here for over a month, and they're still here. I do not know when they can go home, do not see what hope, began to miss home, very sad.

Although the cook is changing the pattern to cook every day, but I feel very nervous, can not eat, sleep also can not sleep. At the thought of eating, I felt nauseous and had to vomit through my throat. Dream of hot pot and KFC, but the hospital cafeteria does not have these. For dinner on February 19th, I ate only one orange and drank a little water.

I cried on the phone with my family. I was devastated. It may be because patients are more serious, the risk of daily work exposure is high, there are also news that some of the hospital director died of infection, his nervous fear. At that time, my grandmother was also sick, at home not to go to the infusion. I called her. I cried. Grandma cried.

On February 21st, I went to work from 9 AM TO 1 noon. I felt like I had to be positive, not negative, so I went to the hotel gym and ran three miles on a treadmill. Later, I would do yoga on the floor every day with a hotel towel.

I was working with the first male nurse from our hospital, a former intensive-care unit who was younger than me. We managed the most severely ill group of patients, from beds 1 to 13, seven of whom were hooked up to a breathing machine.

One patient, who was able to get out of bed to eat and wash his clothes for the first two days, came in with a non-invasive suction machine, a catheter and a gastric tube.

One night, when it was so quiet, the patient kept ringing the Bell, saying he was afraid and thought he was going to die. He was nervous and anxious, and he wanted to be with someone. But as soon as he's in a hurry, his oxygen saturation drops and he aspirates more frequently. He's gasping for air. There's no oxygen.

We taught him to breathe in through his nose until he could no longer breathe in, and then slowly exhale through his mouth. That's how his breathing slowed down.

For patients like this, the doctor basically decides they're dying, but we can't tell him or his family that.

Also on the 21st, the director told us that after the patients with mild illness were transferred to the shelter or discharged from hospital, we would have to admit a large number of the critically ill. Forty of the 46 patients in our ward might need to be aspirated. So the atmosphere of dancing like a shelter, we don't feel it.

Four-hour shift. We've been walking pretty much nonstop.

A patient who thought he might not make it, thought of euthanasia. But this is not allowed in China, so there is no way. He was in his 70s, very sick, sucked mostly by mouth, and breathed the air through his mouth until his lips were chapped and his nose dry. Anyone who's ever survived a hit-and-run is pretty persistent.

I also found that women are more likely to survive than men. Maybe the women are mothers and have to take care of their families, so they are stronger.

Our hospital's top priority right now is to reduce the fatality rate. Other support teams may be tasked with quarantining all infected people from spreading the disease to others. Our job is to heal the worst of them.

Actually, I used to work in hematology, and I have a high mortality rate. I've seen death before, and I expect it. But it's rarely like this: The patient is suffocating in front of you, and you've tried everything you can think of, but you can't bring him back. This feeling of powerlessness, it's breaking down.

Through thick and thin

Once, when our grandmother in bed 35 needed diapers, toilet paper, and wipes, we called her family. But the family said the whole family was in the hospital, and no one could buy them for her. The paramedics took a little of their supplies and gave it to her. Now every time I go to work, I take straws, diapers, wet wipes and the like from my room to the ward for the patients.

Perhaps our hospital is too big, the food supply is not stable, not as good as the shelter.

One day when I got off the night shift, I saw that the patient's breakfast was just a bowl of white rice porridge and a steamed bread with white flour, no pickles and no eggs. Some older people are, but those in their 40s and 50s are not. So, we also bring them some instant noodles, milk, cookies and the like.

Think of this time, they must be very happy to eat instant noodles.

The Grandma Weng Wen you interviewed before lives in my ward. May Be Grandma just in the hospital, no cell phone, and the home lost, Weng Wen has asked a lot of friends to contact me. One night after 9 pm, I helped her connect Weng Wen to the video phone, watching them in the video happy, very happy.

Flowers from a caring person

Now his grandmother turned negative twice, passed the C.T. , and is out of the hospital. I asked her what to do when she got back. Her son is still in the hospital. Can she manage on his own? She said it was fine if the community picked her up, did her own laundry and cooked.

I think the old people here are super strong. Grandma Weng Wen also said she was going to donate blood to save her son. I kept trying to talk her out of it, and then she said no, but I got the feeling she wanted to go. When Grandma Weng Wen was discharged from the hospital, I gave her a candy and a card and gave her a hug. Seeing how happy grandma is, I feel like I've paid my dues these days.

We have set up a temporary party branch here. All the applications for joining the Party have been submitted. We are all thinking positively. One of my colleagues, who was younger than me, has not told her mother that she has come to Wuhan. The nurse I worked with yesterday had lost her voice and her eyes were swollen. She needed sleeping pills to fall asleep.

I'm better now. The chef would make us dumplings, Mung bean soup, crispy meat, the usual northern dishes, as well as spicy and sour radish strips.

On the bus back to the hotel one day, the driver said, the Hubei provincial government gave us all the first-line medical workers a card, within 5 years can visit all the attractions of Hubei free. He also said, wait until the Cherry blossom, we have not back, then take us to see the cherry blossom, eat authentic hot and dry noodles.

Hot, dry noodles and carrot sticks

I'm looking forward to it. I haven't had enough hot and dry noodles.
